<!DOCTYPE assessment PUBLIC "-//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Assessment MathML 2.4//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_assessment_mathml_2_4.dtd"><assessment xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/" id="a2_ph_basic" recommended_attempts="3" max_attempts="3"><title>pH unused questions</title><page id="abc2247c93d24d5f8406fdd4a9601179"><title>Page 1</title><multiple_choice id="ph_basic_q4" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="ab60ef6ae3da342ed99ab7d379be91913">The pH of a solution is a measure of the ________________ the solution.</p></body><input shuffle="false" id="b2cc59c9224d45f79c6071a6395ffbde" labels="false"><choice value="Res1">total of all ions in</choice><choice value="Res2">molecular weight of</choice><choice value="Res3">potential energy of</choice><choice value="Res4">concentration of H<sup>+</sup> ions in</choice><choice value="Res5">concentration of electrons in</choice></input><part id="ed059625078b483fa23ced67cc9df50b"><response match="Res1" score="0"><feedback><p id="ad0fef0350ffe4dea9e746fc3673de64f">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="Res2" score="0"><feedback><p id="acb83630062fc4c6a8b0940b43d866366">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="Res3" score="0"><feedback><p id="aea0c9c54172f470788a7a845efba7fdc">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="Res4" score="10"><feedback><p id="ac448ba40ed404036b6091f36a19218bc">Correct.</p></feedback></response><response match="Res5" score="0"><feedback><p id="ad30d6501d1f949cc8a6057453e5afcc7">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="ph_basic_q3" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="ae5cd049adc1e4f1b8a4a34fa37883bcb">Blueberries grow best in moderately acidic soils. Which of the following would be an appropriate pH of a soil in which blueberries can be expected to grow well?</p></body><input shuffle="false" id="aa45908fac3f41cead69b334bd598968" labels="false"><choice value="Res1">1.2</choice><choice value="Res2">4.8</choice><choice value="Res3">7.0</choice><choice value="Res4">8.3</choice><choice value="Res5">12.0</choice></input><part id="ae4ad2c9d4bc4aee84f06c1b9602814d"><response match="Res1" score="0"><feedback><p id="ac3e04c1a21ba427482a47b080a674abc">Incorrect. pH close to zero is very acidic.</p></feedback></response><response match="Res2" score="10"><feedback><p id="ac9ca523578154836b6232e90ee770ca4">Correct. pH 4.8 is slightly acidic and is close to the pH of black coffee and tomatoes.</p></feedback></response><response match="Res3" score="0"><feedback><p id="aef97d193515b4017af9352102a6fe3e7">Incorrect. pH 7.0 is neutral.</p></feedback></response><response match="Res4" score="0"><feedback><p id="aeb6194227ed54491b30420db78908a04">Incorrect. pH above 7.0 is basic.</p></feedback></response><response match="Res5" score="0"><feedback><p id="ab00454b4ae1e4e2e9dd4ef7bf4bf73f7">Incorrect. pH close to 14 is highly basic.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="ph_basic_q1" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="aec0a2b2d9882413b83cce914b8d9d90b">A solution with a pH of 3.0 has how many hydrogen ions compared to a solution with a pH of 6.0?</p></body><input shuffle="false" id="f364e1b6ef0847b6b2b4be103793f69f" labels="false"><choice value="Res1">half as many</choice><choice value="Res2">two times more</choice><choice value="Res3">1,000 times less</choice><choice value="Res4">100 times more</choice><choice value="Res5">1,000 times more</choice></input><part id="b9db6752f38743479c617da351d65840"><response match="Res1" score="0"><feedback><p id="cbf3963c58194e6083cc6387ab547353">Incorrect. pH is measured in orders of magnitude (10-fold steps).</p></feedback></response><response match="Res2" score="0"><feedback><p id="abf27c622cd9f4635aea0178d18818ebf">Incorrect. pH is measured in orders of magnitude (10-fold steps).</p></feedback></response><response match="Res3" score="0"><feedback><p id="acc96b8c0a34d4d5eaef5cfe67d9bca17">Incorrect. Lower pH indicates more hydrogen ions.</p></feedback></response><response match="Res4" score="0"><feedback><p id="aa1aa1560994049db995e9e96182851ae">Incorrect. The difference between 3.0 and 6.0 is more than two-fold.</p></feedback></response><response match="Res5" score="10"><feedback><p id="acda7655cf8a84998903493fc7284e3e3">Correct. A solution at pH 3.0 has three orders of magnitude, or 1,000 times, more hydrogen ions than a solution at pH 6.0.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice></page></assessment>
